<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-07-04T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-07-04T08:00:00-05:00" n="693" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d693">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00/251: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Callao-Lima</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Handley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-07-04T08:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">July 4,
                                            1919, 8 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received
                                        10.10 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Three o’clock this morning regiments one and two took the Government
                                Palace, imprisoned President Pardo and most of the Cabinet
                                Ministers, and installed Augusto B. Leguia, President of Peru. All
                                conducted without disturbances. Practically no opposition. Rumored
                                Pardo Government had decided nullify Leguia’s election. Army now
                                patrolling Lima. Do not anticipate trouble.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Handley</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>